your_message: To Whom It May Concern,I would like to find some time to meet with you discuss my request in seeking a partnership with you and your organization.ë_ James Campbell High School is restructuring the way we approach the teaching and learning of students to become career and college ready.ë_ We understand that we must develop our students to meet the needs of the business community.ë_ A partnership with your organization would allow JCHS to understand the immediate needs of the workplace and in collaboration with your management team and our academy team, develop best practices for the teaching and training required for our students to be successful not only in your organization but other local area businesses.ë_ Our goal is to provide a first hand experience in an area of their interest and focus, which will lead them to graduating from high school and provide the experience and opportunities necessary to pursue their dreams.ë_ It is vital in the learning experience to provide students with the exposure to a variety if career interests.ë_ They must understand the needs of the career.ë_ Overall, with your commitment, all students from Campbell High will be career and college ready.ë_ The economic reality reflects these converging expectations. Education is more valued and more necessary that ever before. The bottom line is that today ALL high school graduates need to be prepared for some post secondary education and/or training if they are to have options and opportunities in the job market.What is Career Ready-In today_Ñés economy, a _ÑÒcareer_Ñ is not just a job. A career provides a family-sustaining wage and pathways to advancement and requires post secondary training or education. A job may be obtained with only a high school diploma, but offers no guarantee of advancement or mobility. Being ready for a career means that a high school graduate has the English, and mathematics knowledge and skills needed to qualify for and succeed in the post secondary job training and/or education necessary for their chosen career (i.e. technical/vocational program, community college, apprenticeship or significant on-the-job training). What is College Ready-College today means much more than just pursuing a four- year degree at a university. Being _ÑÒcollege ready_Ñ means being prepared for any post secondary education or training experience, including study at two- and four year institutions leading to a post secondary credential (i.e. a certificate, license, Associates or Bachelor_Ñés degree). Being ready for college means that a high school graduate has the English and mathematics knowledge and skills necessary to qualify for and succeed in entry level, credit-bearing college courses without the need for remedial course work.How do we plan to achieve this?ë_ Below are some of the ideas we would like to implement in our academy structure. ë_Guest Speakers / Career Daysë_- We would like the support of your organization in providing speakers for JCHS in the areas in which you hire for employment.ë_ Such areas would be in Business & Marketing, Health Occupations, Culinary, and other opportunities.ë_ Speakers would discuss the requirements for the position, education needed, job demands and how can students be better prepared for positions within your organization.Facility Toursë_- We would love to have some of our classes tour your facilities, we feel being able to visually see the workplace offers a student first hand information of the various jobs that are performed within your organization.ë_ Exposure to the variety of career choices available is vital in a students early years so they can somewhat prepare for a career and college choice.ë_ We do understand that most people change jobs numerous times, but the intent is to expose them to what is available.Job Shadowingë_- We would like to possibly pair up some of our students with employees in your organization that students have selected to witness what is done in that specific career.ë_ Possibly see two or three different jobs within their visit.ë_ The time would be arranged with your organization as well as the number of students you feel you could accommodate.ë_ These would be students who have earned the right to attend.ë_ This experience would be valuable in determining their eventual career choice.Internshipsë_- This would be for the best of the best of our Senior students.ë_ We would like to place a student or two within your organization who might best fit your needs for employment.ë_ This will allow them to achieve on the job training and evaluate their current skill set and identify areas in need of improvement.ë_ This internship may also lead to employment for the student and possibly solidify their career choice.ë_ We would work with your management group to decide what would be the best fit and working agreement to support both of our efforts.ë_ We want it to be a win-win for all.Externshipsë_- We would possibly like to have a teacher do a short-term assignment to gain first hand knowledge of the workplace requirements for your organization, so that they can further develop their teaching and curriculum to meet the needs of the workplace and the skills required for the students.Community Service Projectsë_- We would like to have our academy give back to your organization by assisting with community service projects or other areas in which you need help and we can support.ë_ We want our students to be well rounded and these service projects allow them to get out and be a contributing member of our society.ë_ Its not only about what you can do to help us, but what can we do to help you.ë_ We feel this will better prepare our students to be a well-rounded students and provide the characteristics needed to be successful in life.School-Based Enterprise (SBE)ë_- is an entrepreneurial operation in a school setting that provides goods/services to meet the needs of the market. SBEs are managed and operated by students as hands-on learning laboratories that integrate National Curriculum Standards in marketing, finance, hospitality or management.ë_ SBEs provide realistic and practical learning experiences that reinforce classroom instruction. SBEs can sell to consumers through a permanent location, a mobile kiosk or through Internet marketing.ë_Products may include spirit wear, food and beverage items, school supplies, signs and banners and more, while other SBEs provide services such as creative design, advertising sales and more.ë_ Our goal is to eventually build small school-based business opportunities on campus that would be student run.ë_ Students need to learn the day to day tasks with business operations. Scholarshipsë_- I would like to create an opportunity to develop some scholarships for students in our academy in the Business and Natural Resources Pathways.ë_ Still working on the particulars, but working in conjunction with our business partners, I feel we can create a great award system for those students wishing to go above and beyond and excelling in these areas.ë_ Great way to give back to students doing great things.Please let me know if you have any further questions or concerns and would like to arrange a time to discuss this potential partnership in detail.ë_ We are willing to make it fit your schedule and needs.ë_ We do not want this to impact your organization in a negative way.ë_ We are willing to develop it to meet the needs of your organization.Thank you in advance for your willingness to consider a business partnership with the James Campbell High School.ë_ Together, we can make great things happen.My Dreamë_- My Pathë_- My StoryI look forward to discussing this in further detail when time permits,Shayne Greenland808-253-8510

The patent I chose, and won with, was for an advanced coating that galvanically protects embedded steel rebar from corrosion. I chose this technology because infrastructure in our country is crumbling and needs to preserved due to lack of new investment. I am passionate about solving real problems facing society and corrosion is one of those problems that will never go away. It was all for naught as, in the end, my investor went back on their promises and I had to walk away from the project or continue with low pay and zero share of the company I founded. It was an amazing experience but it was also sharp lesson. I want to take that experience, learn everything I possibly can about cybersecurity/infosec, and eventually launch my own firm after I've acquired some experience working for real players in the industry. From my research, Devleague looks to be an amazing, immersive experience for those looking for such a career boost. I believe I am a great fit for the devleague program as I love technology, I thrive in team-oriented environments, I am a quick study, and I am passionate about making a positive impact on the issues the world is facing. motivation: My name is Jesse Leung. At 28 years old, I am recent graduate of Carnegie Mellon University with a BA in Creative Writing, and I am on a journey of redemption. I see DevLeague as the best way for me to improve my life, and correct the mistakes of my past. I graduated from Punahou School in 2007, and began attending Carnegie Mellon the following fall. For most of my life I had believed I was going to go into the sciences, or engineering. I passed AP Physics and a Java-based AP Computer Science class. But in the summer between my Junior and Senior year of high school, I took a writing class to improve my college application essays. I had the unfortunate pleasure to discover I had a talent for writing, and that I enjoyed the work involved in honing my craft. Despite the fact that I was accepted into the school of Information Systems and the college of Electrical and Computer Engineering, when the time came to choose a college to enroll in at CMU, I chose the highly lucrative major of Creative Writing. Influenced by my hobbies in computer gaming and long nights spent running games of Dungeons and Dragons for my friends, I dreamt of writing stories for game companies like Bioware, Blizzard, Doublefine, and Wizards of the Coast, with a fallback plan of writing for magazines like WIRED or Science until I could achieve such a position. However, when the recession of 2008 hit, the landscape of my dream path was massively altered. Newspapers and Magazines either folded or downsized. Other established writing jobs became much more competitive. Now it was much more likely that as a writer I would have to make a living as a freelancer, selling articles piecemeal with no chance at job security. Then in the winter of that year my grandfather, who had been financially supporting my education, as well as my hanai grandmother who I had known since I was two, passed away. I had already struggled for a long time with anxiety and depression since I was a child; I was the victim of severe bullying (similar to what you might see in the documentary _ÑÉBully_Ñé), which finally caused me to change schools from Iolani to Punahou in 10th grade. Then the emotional blow of never being able to prove myself to my grandfather, and my uncertain professional future, caused me to lose focus and motivation as a writer. My anxiety disorder made even starting major assignments very difficult, and I frequently experienced panic-attacks when writing. I struggled for a few more years, with steadily declining grades, until in 2011 I was suspended from Carnegie Mellon. Because I performed well in my first few semesters at CMU, my GPA didn_Ñét actually require suspension, but when I failed a couple classes my advisors could see my trajectory would not improve without a drastic intervention. I returned home and sought out counseling and medication, and tried enrolling at UH for a semester to prove I could return to CMU. However, I discovered that my anxiety issues had not been resolved, and had the same difficulties in completing work that I did at CMU. I was dejected, and lost all confidence in my abilities as a student. I dropped out of school, and spent the next few years working a variety of jobs. I worked at the Kaimuki YMCA as a counselor; I moved furniture; I was an office assistant; I did inventory and bookkeeping for Nohea Gallery; I spent 7 months as a research assistant doing data entry for the National Center for PTSD; and finally worked as a salesman in the hardware department of Sears Windward Mall for a year and a half, all while continuing with psychological therapy. My time in retail ended up being extremely therapeutic. I am by nature a highly introverted person, and being forced to interact with others, selling a product I had little prior experience with, gave my opportunity to practice managing my anxiety in a day-to-day setting. I was very successful at my job, and was even for a month was the salesman with the highest sales-per-hour in the Hawaii and California region. However, I was still very unhappy with my life situation. The pay was meager compared to the amount of stress and abuse from customers I had to endure. Also, being a high-achiever for most of my youth, I had a hard time accepting my new identity as a college dropout with limited employment potential. In 2016 I re-enrolled at Carnegie Mellon with the goal of completing my degree. It was one of the hardest things I had ever done. Though I had made great improvements, my depression and anxiety never entirely disappeared. However, with hard work, often having to do 2 or 3 all-nighters a week for months at a time, I finally graduated in May of 2017. Though I had limited success as a writer in CMU, receiving a school award and receiving publishing for a creative non-fiction story I had written, I knew I could not endure living as a freelancer, and so began diversifying my abilities. When I returned to CMU I took a drawing class through the CMU school of art, and took a beginner class in Python. When I returned home for the Summer, through personal connections I was offered a job teaching a summer-school class in basic programming with MIT_Ñés SCRATCH to Middle School students at St. Andrew_Ñés Priory. Upon completing the class, I was offered a position to teach the course for the normal school-year at the High School level. However, at this time I don_Ñét feel entirely qualified, and would prefer to improve my programming skills and knowledge in computer science: another reason I chose to apply to DevLeague. I have several friends in the indie gaming industry, and still entertain the dream of working for a game-company. Participating in DevLeague would make me much more employable as a triple-threat with writing, art, and programming skills. Aside from that, being a software engineer would also provide much more financial security than any writing-based work I could get. Should I choose to return to education, completing a DevLeague course would give me the confidence to teach at a higher level. I don_Ñét know if it would be appropriate since I have some prior coding experience, but if it would be helpful I am also interested in taking the upcoming prep-course. I believe that given my life experience and my future aspirations, I am an ideal candidate for DevLeague, and would be a prime example that this training provides access to new and exciting professional avenues that would not otherwise be possible. I look forward to hearing back from you in the near future.
